[stdout] {"type":"text","timestamp":1772768968800,"sessionID":"ses_33ec0745bffeAaiPmxWzb0nioG","part":{"id":"prt_cc143a796001Ar10AfeUsWjpLS","sessionID":"ses_33ec0745bffeAaiPmxWzb0nioG","messageID":"msg_cc143a3d3001Cl7yRQJxF2YaHp","type":"text","text":"Built a minimal RP2040 breakout in `index.circuit.tsx:1` with `routingDisabled` on the board, a USB-C device port, RP2040, 3.3 V LDO, 12 MHz crystal, one status LED, and two 1x20 breakout headers for exposed IO and debug/power pins.\n\n- Used only local/imported JLCPCB parts, not tscircuit registry components: `imports/RP2040.tsx`, `imports/TYPE_C_16PIN_2MD_073_.tsx`, `imports/XC6206P332MR.tsx`, `imports/USBLC6_2P6_MS.tsx`, `imports/XL_1608SYGC_06.tsx`, `imports/A_0603WAF1001T5E.tsx`, `imports/RC0603FR_0727RL.tsx`, `imports/CC0603KRX7R9BB104.tsx`, `imports/A_2_54_1_20P__.tsx`, and a local crystal wrapper in `imports/X322512MSB4SI.tsx:1`.\n- Wired the USB-C connector for basic USB 2.0 device use with CC pulldowns, ESD protection, VBUS into the regulator, USB D+/D- into the RP2040, and common 3.3 V / GND distribution.\n- Exposed GPIO0-19 on `J2`, GPIO20-29 plus `RUN`, `SWCLK`, `SWD`, `3.3V`, `GND`, and key QSPI pins on `J3`, keeping the breakout compact and straightforward.\n- Added the LED on `GPIO25` through a 1 k resistor as a simple onboard indicator.\n- Assumed a minimal breakout scope without external QSPI flash or boot-select/reset buttons, so this is a compact core-board style layout rather than a fully standalone Pico-like design.\n\nArtifacts were generated successfully.\n\n- Build output: `dist/index/circuit.json`\n- Snapshots: `__snapshots__/index.circuit-pcb.snap.svg`, `__snapshots__/index.circuit-schematic.snap.svg`\n\nExecuted successfully:\n\n```bash\ntsci build --site --use-cdn-javascript\ntsci snapshot\n```","time":{"start":1772768968798,"end":1772768968798}}}

